# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the AxisVTU Next.js application.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1
- The package was already listed as a dependency but needed to be installed via npm

### 2. Analytics Integration
Modified `src/app/layout.jsx`:
- Added import: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
- Placed `<Analytics />` component at the end of the `<body>` tag, after the main content
- This follows the official Vercel documentation for Next.js App Router projects

### 3. Files Modified
- `package.json` - Already had @vercel/analytics in dependencies
- `package-lock.json` - Updated with new package installation
- `src/app/layout.jsx` - Added Analytics component import and rendering

## Implementation Details

The Analytics component was added to the root layout file (`src/app/layout.jsx`) which ensures it runs on every page of the application. This is the recommended approach for Next.js App Router applications according to the official Vercel documentation.

The component is placed at the end of the body tag to:
1. Ensure it doesn't block page rendering
2. Allow it to collect analytics data for all pages
3. Follow Vercel's recommended best practices

## Verification

- Build completed successfully with no errors
- All 33 pages were generated successfully
- The Analytics component will automatically start collecting data when deployed to Vercel

## Next Steps

To enable analytics data collection:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Navigate to the Vercel Dashboard → Analytics
3. Enable Web Analytics for the project
4. Analytics data will start appearing in the dashboard after deployment

Note: Analytics will only collect data in production environments by default. For local testing, you can use the debug mode: `<Analytics debug={true} />`
